    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i was looking at my mortgage statement and it's super confusing. i have a 30 year fixed at 6.5% on a $400,000 loan. i know my monthly payment is roughly $2528 but i'm trying to figure out how much of that is actually hitting the principal vs interest. like, if i look at year 5 compared to year 25, is there a huge difference in how much interest i'm paying each month? can u break down how that actually works?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, there is a significant difference between year 5 and year 25 in how your payment is split. In the early years, a larger portion of your monthly payment goes toward interest because the outstanding loan balance is very high. As you pay down the principal, the amount of interest charged each month decreases, meaning more of your fixed payment then goes toward actually reducing the loan balance. Essentially, the interest portion shrinks as the principal shrinks.",
